05339nam a22007215i 9780823296576DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20221995nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232965767 a10.1515/97808232965762doi  a(DE-B1597)626421  a(OCoLC)1322124709  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLIT0040202bisacsh1 aBrophy, Robert J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRobinson Jeffers :bThe Dimensions of a Poet /cRobert J. Brophy. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©1995  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1 Robinson Jeffers: Poet of Carmel-Sur -- t2 In the Poet's Lifetime -- t3 Robinson Jeffers and the Uses of History -- t4 Telling the Past and Living the Present: "Thurso's Landing" and the Epic Tradition -- t5 Jeffers's "Roan Stallion" and the Narrative of Nature -- t6 "Divinely Superfluous Beauty": Robinson Jeffers's Versecraft of the Sublime -- t7 Robinson Jeffers and the Female Archetype -- t8 Desire, Death, and Domesticity in Jeffers's Pastorals of Apocalypse -- t9 Nature and the Symbolic Order: The Dialogue Between Czeslaw Milosz and Robinson Jeffers -- t10 All Flesh Is Grass -- tA Review of Jeffers Scholarship -- tWorks by Robinson Jeffers: A Chronological Listing -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAmerican Poet Robinson Jeffers (1887-1962) was educated in the classics from an early age and published his first book of poetry in 1912. Most of Jeffers' work is distinguished by strong elemental narratives set in the California Carmel/Big Sur area. His imagery often puts the rugged beauty of the landscape in opposition to the degraded and introverted condition of modern humanity. Jeffers' themes draw on classical and biblical sources from his early education, and his strong interest in Nietzsche's concept of individualism. Many of his contemporaries erroneously regarded him as a nihilist. This collection of essays attempts to illustrate the art and complexity of Jeffers, while presenting new insights into his work and its perception among his contemporaries. The essayists are Robert Brophy, Alex Vardamis, Robert Zaller, Terry Beers, Tim Hunt, David J. Rothman, Alan Soldofsky, Kirk Glaser, and William Everson. The essays represent a range of critical points of entry-some are on the cutting-edge of criticism and break new ground, others attempt to place Jeffers in the established perspectives of Western civilization's Christian humanism and American poetry's landscape-centered mysticism. The collection constitutes some of the most conversant and active research in the field of Jeffers studies. The critiques speak to the nature of Jeffer's poetry- how it challenged both the minds and hearts of its readers and prompted them to carefully define their own values and authentically find their own center.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh1 aBeers, Terry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrophy, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEverson, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlaser, Kirk, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHunt, Tim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRothman, David J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSoldofsky, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVardamis, Alex, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZaller, Robert, econtributor.4ctb